04653nam a22006975i 9781487595241DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20191961onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814875952417 a10.3138/97814875952412doi  a(DE-B1597)513996  a(OCoLC)1091658840  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 4aPR4147b.F5 1961 7aLIT0041202bisacsh04a821/.72231 aFisher, Peter, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Valley of Vision :bBlake as Prophet and Revolutionary /cPeter Fisher; ed. by Northrop Frye. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2019] 4cÂ©1961  a1 online resource (278 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aHeritage00tFrontmatter -- tEditor's Preface -- tAuthor's Preface -- tContents -- t1. The Prophetic Reprobate -- t2. The Circle of Destiny -- t3. The Allegory of the Church -- t4. Reason and the New Science -- t5. The Critique of Vision -- t6. Enthusiasm and the Romantic Revolt -- t7. Visionary Politics -- t8. Genius and Imagination: The Alchemy of Vision -- t9. The Prelude to Prophecy -- t10. Human Existence: The Epic Theme -- t11. Natural Existence: The Selfhood -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe author of this important contribution to the study of Blake was tragically drowned in a sailing accident when he had almost completed it in manuscript. His was a critical mind of singular erudition and power. As is abundantly evidenced in these chapters which Northrop Frye has prepared for publication. Fisher had made a careful study of Oriental philosophy and of Plato and the Neo-Platonists and this background enabled him to make an original and fruitful analysis of his central interest, Blake. The book is not a study of Blake's sources but of his context. The author is trying to answer the question: given Blake's general point of view, why does he make the specific judgments he does make, judgments which so often seem merely glib or petulant or perverse. Blake himself, in explaining a painting, remarked: "It ought to be understood that the Persons, Moses & Abraham, are not here meant, but the States Signified by those Names." Fisher explains what Blake meant by "states," and shows that such names as Plato, Bacon or Newton, or such terms as "priest" or "deist" in Blake's writings, refer not to individuals but to cultural forces in Western civilization, the influence of which accounted for the social conditions that Blake attacked. The attack itself, Fisher shows, was based on a revolutionary dialectic, a sense of the underlying opposition between reactionaries committed to obscurantism and social injustice, the "Elect" as Blake calls them, and the prophets committed to a greater vision (the "Reprobate"), with the mass of the public (the "Redeemed") in between.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aProphecies in literature. 0aRevolutionary literature, EnglishxHistory and criticism. 0aVisions in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh1 aFrye, Northrop, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press eBook-Package Archive 1933-1999z978311049094740uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148759524140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487595241423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781487595241.jpg  a978-3-11-049094-7  University of Toronto Press eBook-Package Archive 1933-1999c1933d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK